data.text: Mersch: The ECB cannot, at this stage, consider basing our market infrastructure on a distributed ledger solution
Mersch: Work ongoing in 3 areas: consolidation TARGET2 & T2S, settlement services to support instant payments, collateral management system
Mersch: Exploration of technological innovation high on ECB’s agenda, as it always wants to lower the costs of its market infrastructure

Draghi: With our policies we are lowering risk that current low rates of growth become entrenched. But we alone cannot eliminate that risk.
Draghi: Without concerted effort on structural reforms, per capita income growth in euro area is likely to stagnate or even decline
Draghi: Preliminary internal ECB research and anecdotal evidence finds that lower interest rates tend to support rather than hinder reforms
Draghi: Breaking down duality in labour market enables the unemployed youth of today to become the high-skilled older workers of the future
Draghi: Reforms in Spain in mid-2012 are example of a structural reform that has been successful in unblocking the labour market
Draghi: Adequate institutional frameworks, such as bankruptcy laws, needed to ensure capital is not trapped in unproductive or failed firms
Charts belonging to the speech of Mario Draghi are here https://t.co/l9QSNo8d7P
Draghi: Structural reforms make the euro area economy more resilient against the disruptive influence of globalisation and digitalisation
Draghi: Structural reforms also help fully unlock benefits of Single Market and thereby improve cohesiveness of the monetary union
Draghi: Stronger potential output growth reduces likelihood that unconventional measures will be required to counteract future downturns
Draghi: Structural reforms are therefore urgently needed to raise productivity growth and unlock unused labour potential
Draghi: Slow productivity growth impacts future prosperity and will have consequences for monetary and fiscal policy and euro area cohesion

Draghi: The European Union has to deliver on key objectives from the citizens’ perspective to regain trust in the European project
Draghi: The Single Market cannot go backwards. It is in fact essential to further strengthen and develop the Single Market.
Draghi: It is important to have clarity on the UK exit negotiation process as soon as possible in order to reduce uncertainty
Draghi: The Single Market has been a positive sum game because it allows the EU to reap efficiency gains and better satisfy demand
Draghi: EMU will have to overcome vulnerabilities from its incompleteness. A half-built house is not stable, it is fragile
Draghi: Smaller firms also benefit from our measures via lower borrowing costs from banks and via increased lending capacity of banks
Draghi: Low ECB interest rates, favourable lending conditions in our TLTROs and our asset purchases have resulted in lower borrowing costs
Draghi: ECB’s monetary stimulus has been a key ingredient of the recovery
